1. Terminal Basics
Command	Purpose	Example
ls	List files	ls
ls -al	List all, including hidden	ls -al
cd <folder>	Change directory	cd ~/Bioinformatics
mkdir <folder>	Make new folder	mkdir SubFolder
touch <file>	Create empty file	touch NewFile.txt
echo "text" > file	Create file with content	echo "Hello World" > NewFile.txt
cat <file>	Show file content	cat NewFile.txt

2. Git Basics
Command	Purpose	Example
git status	Check file status	git status
git add <file>	Stage a file	git add NewFile.txt
git add .	Stage all changes	git add .
git commit -m "message"	Commit staged changes	git commit -m "Add NewFile.txt"
git push origin <branch>	Push to GitHub	git push origin main
git log --oneline -5	Show last 5 commits	git log --oneline -5

3. Branches
Command	Purpose	Example
git branch	List branches	git branch
git checkout <branch>	Switch branch	git checkout dev
git push origin <branch>	Push branch	git push origin dev
4. SSH Key Setup

Generate key:

ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "isaacnewtonswesco@gmail.com"

Show public key:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

Add to GitHub → Settings → SSH and GPG keys → New SSH key

Test connection:

ssh -T git@github.com

Expected: Hi Isaac-Newton-Odei-Asare! You've successfully authenticated...

5. Uploading Files to GitHub
Add a file
echo "This is a new file" > NewFile.txt
git add NewFile.txt
git commit -m "Add NewFile.txt"
git push origin main
Add a file in a subfolder
mkdir -p SubFolder
echo "Content in subfolder" > SubFolder/File.txt
git add SubFolder/File.txt
git commit -m "Add File.txt to SubFolder"
git push origin main

Tip: Don’t commit .ssh or private keys. Use .gitignore for sensitive files.

6. Working from a Different PC

Install Git and set identity:

git config --global user.name "Isaac-Newton-Odei-Asare"
git config --global user.email "isaacnewtonswesco@gmail.com"

Generate SSH key and add to GitHub (see above)

Clone your repo:

git clone git@github.com:Isaac-Newton-Odei-Asare/Bioinformatics.git
cd Bioinformatics

Pull latest changes before work:

git pull origin main

Stage, commit, and push changes:

git add .
git commit -m "Your commit message"
git push origin main
7. Key Notes

Commit → Push workflow

Always know your branch

SSH key setup is one-time per machine

File/folder structure on Ubuntu is preserved on GitHub

Use git status often to track changes
